    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1547879389,
    "last_edit_date" : 1547879389,
    "creation_date" : 1547877314,
    "answer_id" : 54264467,
    "question_id" : 5323502,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As mentioned above, the following <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/java8locales-2095355.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">link</a> gives you the specific country code to allow Java to localize the number. Every country has its own style. </p>\n\n<p>In the link above you will find the country code which should be placed in here:</p>\n\n<pre><code>...(new Locale(&lt;COUNTRY CODE HERE&gt;));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Switzerland for example formats the numbers as follows:</p>\n\n<p>1000.00 --> 1'000.00</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/lbBSZ.png\" rel=\"noreferrer\">country code</a></p>\n\n<p>To achieve this, following <strong>codes</strong> works for me:</p>\n\n<pre><code>NumberFormat nf = NumberFormat.getNumberInstance(new Locale(\"de\",\"CH\"));\nnf.setMaximumFractionDigits(2);\nDecimalFormat df = (DecimalFormat)nf;\nSystem.out.println(df.format(1000.00));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Result is as expected:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>1'000.00\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
